<div id="hdr">
<div style="text-align: right; width: 100%"><font style="font-family: Times New 
Roman; font-size: 11px">&#xA0;</font></div></div></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">
<br></font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">LIQUIDITY AND 
CAPITAL RESOURCES</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">At June 30, 
2016 we had cash on hand of $11,973 compared to $108 at December 31, 2015. We 
used cash in our operations of $(210,986) in 2016 compared to cash used of 
$(51,882) in 2015. We generated cash-flow from investing activities during 2016 
of $74,559, compared to $0 for the same quarter in 2015. We (paid back)/raised
$(224,600) and $9,935 from related party loans in
2016 and 2015, and $3,000 and $40,700 from other notes payable, respectively. We
also collected $370,000 from the receipt of stock subscriptions during the six 
month period of 2016 compared to $0 in the prior year. We anticipate that we 
will continue to have a negative cash flow from operations of approximately 
$15,000 per month for 2016. We do not have sufficient cash on hand at June 30, 
2016 to cover our negative cash flow. We will attempt to increase our revenues 
from oil &amp; gas extraction when oil prices
increase, and raise capital through the sale of our common stock or through debt
financing, or engaging in other operations.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Some of Global 
Tech&#x2019;s past due obligations, including $338,000 of accounts payable, and 
$113,000 of notes payable and judgments, some of which are duplicative, were 
incurred or obtained prior to 2005. No actions have been taken by any of the 
applicable creditors, and the statute of limitations has been exceeded for the 
creditors to seek legal action. Global Tech believes
that these obligations will not be satisfied in the future because the statute 
of limitations has been exceeded, but is not allowed to remove them from our 
books and records due to accounting regulations.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">During the six 
months ended June 30, 2016, the Company&#x2019;s working capital deficit 
decreased from $(3,215,878) to $(1,939,855), a decrease of 40%, due to the 
extension of several long term notes that had become current or in default. If 
the old payables and notes that have exceeded the statute of limitations were 
removed from the calculation, the working capital deficit
would be $(1,488,855), a 54% decrease over 2015.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Any remedy to 
our current lack of liquidity must take into account all the foregoing 
liabilities. Global Tech intends to continue its pursuit to increase revenues 
from our oil generating leases when oil prices improve, or find other operating 
activities, and as necessary, raise capital in order to monetize its business 
and pay all its liabilities. Capital raise plans are
under consideration but it cannot be assured that they will materialize in the 
current economic environment. Currently, Global Tech is without adequate 
financing or assets. Because no actions have been taken on the aforementioned 
past due obligations and demand has not been made by the applicable current note
holders, we are unable to accurately quantify the effect the overdue accounts 
have on Global Tech&#x2019;s financial condition, liquidity and capital 
resources. However, in the event that all of these obligations
and notes payable were required to be paid in an amount equal to the full 
balance of each, Global Tech would not be able to meet the obligations based 
upon its current financial status. The liquidity shortfall of $(1,939,855) would
cause Global Tech to default and, further, would put our continued viability in 
jeopardy.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">CONTRACTUAL 
OBLIGATIONS</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size:
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">None</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-weight: bold; font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Going Concern 
Qualification</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">The Company has
incurred significant losses from operations, and such&#xA0;losses are expected 
to continue. The Company's auditors have included a "Going&#xA0;Concern 
Qualification" in their report for the year ended December 31, 2015. 
In&#xA0;addition, the Company has limited working capital. The foregoing 
raises&#xA0;substantial doubt about the Company's ability to continue
as a going concern.&#xA0;Management's plans include seeking additional capital 
and/or debt financing.&#xA0;There is no guarantee that additional capital and/or
debt financing will be&#xA0;available when and to the extent required, or that 
if available, it will be on&#xA0;terms acceptable to the Company. The financial 
statements do not include any&#xA0;adjustments that might result from the 
outcome of this uncertainty. The "Going&#xA0;Concern Qualification" may make it 
substantially more difficult to raise&#xA0;capital.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Off-Balance 
Sheet Arrangements</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">We have no off-
balance sheet arrangements.</font></div>

<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent:
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">ITEM 3.&#xA0; 
QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Not 
Applicable.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-weight: bold; font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">ITEM 4.&#xA0; 
CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Evaluation of 
Disclosure Controls and Procedures</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Disclosure 
controls and procedures are controls and other procedures that are designed to 
ensure that information we are required to disclose is recorded, processed, 
summarized and reported, within the time periods specified in the rules and 
forms of the Commission. David Reichman, our Chief Executive Officer and our 
Principal Accounting Officer, is responsible for establishing
and maintaining our disclosure controls and procedures.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Under the 
supervision and with the participation of our management, including the Chief 
Executive Officer and Principal Accounting Officer, we have evaluated the 
effectiveness of our disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rule 13a-
15(e) and Rule 15d-15(e) of the Exchange Act) as of the end of the period 
covered by this report. Based on that evaluation, the Chief
Executive Officer and Principal Accounting Officer has concluded that, as of 
June 30, 2016 these disclosure controls and procedures were ineffective to 
ensure that all information required to be disclosed by us in the reports that 
we file or submit under the Exchange Act is: (i) recorded, processed, summarized
and reported, within the time periods specified in the Commission&#x2019;s rule 
and forms; and (ii) accumulated and communicated to our management, including 
our Chief Executive Officer and Principal Accounting
Officer, as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding required 
disclosure.&#xA0;The Company&#x2019;s controls are not effective due to a lack 
of the segregation of duties.&#xA0;The Company lacks the appropriate personnel 
to handle all the varying recording and reporting tasks on a timely 
basis.&#xA0;&#xA0;The Company plans to address these material weaknesses as 
resources become available by hiring additional professional staff, such as a 
Chief Financial Officer, as funding becomes available, outsourcing
certain aspects of the recording and reporting functions, and separating 
responsibilities.&#xA0;The Company believes that it would require approximately 
$250,000 per year in available funds in order to retain the qualified personnel 
required for effective disclosure controls and procedures.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">The term
&#x201C;internal control over financial reporting&#x201D; is defined as a 
process designed by, or under the supervision of, the registrant&#x2019;s 
principal executive and principal financial officers, or persons performing 
similar functions, and effected by the registrant&#x2019;s board of directors, 
management and other personnel, to provide reasonable assurance regarding
the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial 
statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted 
accounting principles and includes those policies and procedures 
that:</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div>

border-right: 1pt solid #BFBFBF; border-top: 1pt solid #BFBFBF; border-bottom: 
2px solid #bfbfbf">
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">provide
reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized 
acquisition, use or disposition of the registrant&#x2019;s assets that could 
have a material effect on the financial 
statements.</font></div></td></tr></table></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Changes
in Internal Controls over Financial Reporting</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">There 
were no additional changes in our internal control over financial reporting that
occurred during the fiscal quarter ended June 30, 2016 that has materially 
affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, our internal control 
over financial reporting.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">Inherent Limitations over Internal Controls</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Global 
Tech&#x2019;s management does not expect that its disclosure controls or its 
internal control over financial reporting will prevent or detect all error and 
all fraud. A control system, no matter how well designed and operated, can 
provide only reasonable, not absolute, assurance that the control 
system&#x2019;s objectives will be met. The design of a control system
must reflect the fact that there are resource constraints, and the benefits of 
controls must be considered relative to their costs. Further, because of the 
inherent limitations in all control systems, no evaluation of controls can 
provide absolute assurance that misstatements due to error or fraud will not 
occur or that all control issues&#xA0;and instances of fraud, if any, within 
Global Tech have been detected. These inherent limitations include the realities
that judgments in decision making can be faulty
and that breakdowns can occur because of simple error or mistake. Controls can 
also be circumvented by the&#xA0;individual acts of some persons, by collusion 
of two or more people, or management override of the controls. The design of any
system of controls is based in part on certain assumptions about the likelihood 
of future events, and there can be no assurance&#xA0;that any design will 
succeed in achieving its stated goals under all potential future conditions. 
Projections of any evaluation of controls effectiveness
to future periods are subject to risks. Over time, controls may become 
inadequate because of changes&#xA0;in conditions or deterioration in the degree 
of compliance with policies or procedures.</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">Our 
disclosure controls and procedures are designed to provide reasonable assurance 
of that our reports will be accurate. Our Chief Executive Officer and Principal 
Accounting Officer concludes that our disclosure controls and procedures were
ineffective at that reasonable assurance level, as of the end of the period 
covered by this Form 10-Q. Our future reports shall also
indicate that our disclosure controls and procedures are designed for this 
reason and shall indicate the related conclusion by the Chief Executive Officer 
and Principal Accounting Officer as to their effectiveness.</font></div>

right: 0px">

Roman; font-size: 11px">&#xA0;</font></div>

background-color: #000000">

</div>
<div id="hdr">
<div style="text-align: right; width: 100%"><font style="font-family: Times New 
Roman; font-size: 11px">&#xA0;</font></div></div></div>
<div style="text-align: justify; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-weight: bold; font-family: Times New Roman; font-
size: 13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: center; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">PART 
II&#xA0;OTHER INFORMATION</font></div>
<div style="text-align: center; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-
indent: 0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">ITEM 1.&#xA0; 
LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
48px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">During March 
2013, the Company was named in an action pertaining to the 75% working interest 
in the Ownbey Lease.<font style="color: #1F497D">&#xA0;</font>Subsequent to the 
Company&#x2019;s purchase of the assets and the termination of the operator a 
mechanics lien was filed against the property claiming approximately $267,000 in
fees are due to the previous operator. An
action is pending in the District Court of Chautauqua County, Kansas, captioned 
<font style="text-decoration: underline">Aesir Energy, Inc. vs. Amercian 
Resource Technologies, Inc.; Nancy Ownbey Archer; Jimmy Stephen Ownbey; Robbie 
Faye Butts; TREE TOP INDUSTRIES, INC.; and TTII oil &amp; Gas, Inc.</font> 
Management intends to vigorously contest AESIR&#x2019;s claims and, at this 
point, settlement appears unlikely. It has been presented in the County Court 
that some of ARUR&#x2019;s Directors have acted without
authorization in this matter, and Global Tech&#x2019;s management is assessing 
how to proceed at this time. No monetary claims have been asserted against 
Global Tech or TTII Oil &amp; Gas, Inc. <font style="font-family: Times New 
Roman; font-size: 13px">The District Court of Chautauqua County, Kansas decided 
that the Board of American Resource Technologies, Inc., acted improperly and set
aside the Acquisition Agreement as null and void. Management is consulting with 
legal counsel to evaluate the company options.</font></font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
0px"><font style="font-weight: bold; font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>
<div style="text-align: left; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-indent: 
48px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 13px">ITEM 2.&#xA0;

0px"><font style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; font-family: Times New

for any of these notes has been received by the Company. However,&#xA0;the 
Company received a notice of motion from Luckysurf.com dated October 22, 2002, 
seeking entry of a judgment for $30,000. No further information or action has 
been received by the Company relating to this note.</font></div>

have a significant role in the small business issuer&#x2019;s internal control 
over financial reporting.</font></div></td></tr></table></div>

0px"><font style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 
13px">&#xA0;</font></div>

prepared;</font></div></td></tr></table></div>

of&#13;operations, and cash flows at June 30, 2016, and for all periods

    <us-gaap:SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-
01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0;
text-align: justify"&gt;The Company's financial statements are 
prepared&#13;using generally accepted accounting principles in the United States
of America applicable to a going concern which contemplates&#13;the realization 
of assets and liquidation of liabilities in the normal course of business. The 
Company has not yet established&#13;an ongoing source of revenues sufficient to 
cover its operating costs and allow it to continue as a going concern. The 
ability&#13;of the Company to continue as a going concern is dependent on the 
Company obtaining adequate capital to fund operating losses until&#13;it becomes
profitable. If the Company is unable to obtain adequate capital, it could be 
forced to cease operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In order to continue as a going
concern, the&#13;Company will need, among other things, additional capital 
resources. Management's plan is to obtain such resources for the Company&#13;by 
obtaining capital from management and significant shareholders sufficient to 
meet its&amp;#160;operating expenses and seeking equity&#13;and/or debt 
financing. However management cannot provide any assurances that the Company
will be successful in accomplishing any&#13;of its 
plans.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The ability of the Company to 
continue as a&#13;going concern is dependent upon its ability to successfully 
accomplish the plans described in the preceding paragraph and 
eventually&#13;secure other sources of financing and attain profitable 
operations. The accompanying financial statements do not include any 
adjustments&#13;that might be necessary if the Company is unable to continue as 
a going concern.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:SubstantialDoubtAboutGoingConcernTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-
01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0;
text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Use of 
Estimates&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The preparation of financial 
statements in conformity&#13;with accounting principles generally accepted in 
the United States of America requires management to make estimates and 
assumptions&#13;that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at 
the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of&#13;revenue and
expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those 
estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Beneficial Conversion Feature of Debentures and 
Convertible Notes&#13;Payable&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;In accordance with FASB ASC 470-20, 
Accounting for Convertible Securities&#13;with Beneficial Conversion Features or
Contingently Adjustable Conversion Ratios, we recognize the advantageous value 
of conversion&#13;rights attached to convertible debt.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Such 
rights give the debt holder the ability to convert his debt into common 
stock&#13;at a price per share that is less than the trading price to the public
on the day the loan is made to us. The beneficial value&#13;is calculated as the
intrinsic value (the market price of the stock at the commitment date in excess 
of the conversion rate) of&#13;the beneficial conversion feature of the 
debentures and related accruing interest, and is recorded as a discount to the 
related&#13;debt and an addition to additional paid in 
capital.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The discount is amortized over the remaining 
outstanding period&#13;of related debt using the straight-line 
method.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Recent Accounting 
Pronouncements&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times,
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;No accounting pronouncements were issued during the second 
quarter&#13;of 2016 that would have a material effect on the accounting policies
of the Company when adopted.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Oil and Gas 
Interests&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company utilizes the full cost method of accounting for
oil and&#13;gas activities. Under this method, subject to a limitation based on 
estimated value, all costs associated with property acquisition,&#13;exploration
and development, including costs of unsuccessful exploration; are capitalized 
within a cost center. No gain or loss&#13;is recognized upon the sale or 
abandonment of undeveloped or producing oil and gas interests unless the sale 
represents a significant&#13;portion of oil and gas interests and the gain 
significantly alters the relationship between capitalized costs and proved oil 
and&#13;gas reserves of the cost center. Depreciation, depletion and 
amortization of oil and gas interests are computed on the units 
of&#13;production method based on proved reserves. Amortizable costs include 
estimates of future development costs of proved 
undeveloped&#13;reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Capitalized costs of oil and gas interests may not 
exceed an amount&#13;equal to the present value, discounted at 10%, of the 
estimated future net cash flows from proved oil and gas reserves plus 
the&#13;cost, or estimated fair market value, if lower, of unproved interests. 
Should capitalized costs exceed this ceiling, an impairment&#13;is recognized. 
The present value of estimated future net cash flows is computed by applying 
average prices, in the preceding twelve&#13;months, of oil and gas to estimated 
future production of proved oil and gas reserves as of year-end, less estimated 
future expenditures&#13;to be incurred in developing and producing the proved 
reserves and assuming continuation of existing economic 
conditions.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The oil and gas interests were purchased with the 
issuance of 46,685,300&#13;shares and were valued at market value at the grant 
date as $513,538. However at December 31, 2012, due to a mechanics lien 
and&#13;impairment of title to the assets, the Company impaired the recorded 
cost, leaving no value associated with the acquisition. The&#13;Company recorded
an impairment on long lived assets in the amount of 
$513,538.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Asset Retirement Obligation&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company 
follows FASB ASC 410-20&lt;i&gt; &amp;#34;Accounting for Asset&#13;Retirement 
Obligations,&amp;#34;&lt;/i&gt; which addresses financial accounting and 
reporting for obligations associated with the retirement&#13;of tangible long-
lived assets and the associated asset retirement costs.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; 
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;FASB ASC 410-20 requires 
recognition of the present value of obligations&#13;associated with the 
retirement of tangible long-lived assets in the period in which it is incurred. 
The liability is capitalized&#13;as part of the related long-lived asset's 
carrying amount.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Over time, accretion of the liability is recognized 
as an operating&#13;expense and the capitalized cost is depreciated over the 
expected useful life of the related asset. The Company's asset 
retirement&#13;obligations are related to the plugging, dismantlement, removal, 
site reclamation and similar activities of its oil and gas 
exploration&#13;activities.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; width: 
100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;

Cost&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;The Company&amp;#160;accounts for its investment in private 
entities&#13;using the equity method for investments where the 
Company&amp;#146;s shares held are in excess of 20% of the 
outstanding&amp;#160;shares&#13;of the investee.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company 
acquired a 25% equity investment in three entities from Brazil as part of the 
assets of&#13;the ARUR acquisition in December 2012. Due to the inactivity of 
the entities, the Company did not allocate any purchase price to&#13;these 
investments. The Company evaluates&amp;#160;its cost in investments for 
impairment of value annually.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If cost investments&#13;become 
marketable they are&amp;#160;reclassified to Marketable Securities-Available for
Sale.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;

&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Marketable Securities-Available for 
Sale&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;The Company purchased marketable securities during 2012, 2015 
and&#13;2016. The Company's marketable securities are classified as 
&amp;#34;available for sale&amp;#34;. Accordingly, the Company 
originally&#13;recognizes the shares at the market value purchased. The shares 
are evaluated quarterly using the specific identification method.&#13;Any 
unrealized holding gains or losses are reported as Other Comprehensive Income 
and as a separate component of stockholder's&#13;equity. Realized gains and 
losses are included in earnings. Also other than temporary impairments are 
recorded as a loss on marketable&#13;securities in the statements of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align:

&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Fair Value of 
Financial Instruments&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;On January 1, 2008, the Company adopted ASC 820, 
&amp;#147;Fair Value&#13;Measurements&amp;#148;&lt;i&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/i&gt;ASC 
820 defines fair value, establishes a three-level valuation hierarchy for 
disclosures of fair&#13;value measurement and enhances disclosure requirements 
for fair value measures. The three levels are defined as 
follows:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table
cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
width: 100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt 
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt 
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&#13;        &lt;p style="font: 8pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;o&lt;/p&gt;&#13;        &lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; 
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 94%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt 
solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt 
solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Level 1 inputs to the valuation 
methodology are quoted prices (unadjusted) for identical assets or liabilities 
in active 
markets.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; width:

style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt 
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;o&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 94%; border-top: 
#BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;Level 2 inputs to the valuation methodology include quoted prices for 
similar assets and liabilities in active markets, and inputs that are observable
for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly, for substantially the
full term of the financial 
instrument.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; width: 
100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: top"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt 
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt 
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;o&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 94%; border-top: 
#BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt
solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;Level 3 inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and 
significant to the fair 
measurement.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The carrying amounts reported in the balance sheets 
for cash and&#13;cash equivalents, and current liabilities each qualify as 
financial instruments and are a reasonable estimate of fair value because&#13;of
the short period of time between the origination of such instruments and their 
expected realization and their current market&#13;rate of interest. The carrying
value of notes payable approximates fair value because negotiated terms and 
conditions are consistent&#13;with current market rates as of June 30, 2016 and 
December 31, 2015.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Marketable securities are reported at the quoted and
listed market&#13;rates of the securities held at the period 
end.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-indent: 45pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The following

style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;The accompanying consolidated financial statements&#13;include the 
accounts of the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiaries, NetThruster, Inc., 
BioEnergy Applied Technologies Inc.,&#13;GoHealthMD, Inc., MLN, Inc., Eye Care 
Centers International, Inc., GoHealthMD Nano Pharmaceuticals, Inc., TTI 
Strategic Acquisitions&#13;and&amp;#160;Equity Group, Inc.&amp;#160;and TTII Oil
&amp;#38; Gas, Inc.&amp;#160;All subsidiaries of the Company except TTII Oil 
&amp;#38; Gas, Inc.,&#13;currently have no financial activity. All significant 
inter-company balances and transactions have been 
eliminated.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company 
considers all highly liquid investments with an original&#13;maturity of three 
months or less to be cash equivalents. Cash and cash equivalents are maintained 
with major financial institutions&#13;in the U S. Deposits held with these banks
at times exceed $250,000 of insurance provided on such deposits. The Company has
not&#13;experienced any losses in such accounts and believes that it is not 
exposed to any significant credit risk on cash and cash equivalents.&#13;There 
were no cash equivalents at June 30, 2016 and December 31, 
2015.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Accounts Receivable/Allowances for Doubtful 
Accounts&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company regularly assesses the collectability of its 
accounts&#13;receivable, and considers receivables with aging exceeding 120 days
to be potentially uncollectible. Management will analyze the&#13;need for an 
allowance for doubtful accounts at that time. As of June 30, 2016 and December 
31, 2015, there are no allowances recorded.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; 
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Stock Based 
Compensation&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company accounts for stock-based compensation in 
accordance with&#13;the provisions of ASC 718.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;ASC 718 
requires all share-based payments to employees, including grants of employee 
stock&#13;options, to be recognized in the financial statements based on the 
grant-date fair value of the award. That cost will be recognized&#13;over the 
period during which an employee is required to provide service in exchange for 
the reward- known as the requisite service&#13;period. No compensation cost is 
recognized for equity instruments for which employees do not render the 
requisite service. The&#13;grant-date fair value of employee share options and 
similar instruments are estimated using the Black Scholes option-pricing 
model&#13;adjusted for the unique characteristics of those 
instruments.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Equity instruments issued to 
non-employees
 are&#13;recorded at their fair values as determined in accordance with ASC 718 
and ASC 595, &amp;#147;Accounting for Equity Instruments That&#13;Are Issued to 
Other Than Employees for Acquiring, or in Conjunction with Selling Goods and 
Services&amp;#148;, and are periodically&#13;revalued as the stock options vest 
and are recognized as expense over the related service 
period.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Basic and Diluted Loss per 
Share&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0"&gt;The Company calculates earnings per share in accordance with 
ASC&#13;260, &amp;#147;Computation of Earnings Per Share.&amp;#148; Basic loss 
per share is computed by dividing net income (loss) by the weighted-
average&#13;number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. 
Diluted earnings (loss) per share gives effect to dilutive 
convertible&#13;securities, options, warrants and other potential common stock 
outstanding during the period; only in periods in which such effect&#13;is 
dilutive. For 2016 and 2015, no common equivalent shares were excluded from the 
calculation and as of June 30, 2016, there are&#13;not stock equivalents
existing. The ESOP shares issued during 2012 and 2011 have also been excluded 
from the calculation as they&#13;were issued but not 
outstanding.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; width: 
100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt 
solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="2" style="border-bottom:
#BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;For the Six months&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    
&lt;td style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="2" style="border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: 
center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;For the Six 
Months&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: 
bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt 
solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="2" style="border-bottom:
#BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Ended June 30,&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="2" style="border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: 
center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Ended June 
30,&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom:

+&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom:

style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Basic and diluted income (loss) per 
share&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt

&lt;td style="border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: right"&gt;&lt;font 
style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;(0.00&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td

&lt;td style="border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: right"&gt;&lt;font 
style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;(0.00&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Revenue 
Recognition&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Oil and Gas Revenues and Deferred 
Revenue&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Revenue form sales of crude oil are recorded 
when deliveries have&#13;occurred and legal ownership of the commodity transfers
to the customer. Title transfers for crude oil generally occur when a 
tanker&#13;lifting has occurred. Oil inventory in holding tanks at the period 
end are recorded as deferred revenue prior to tanker 
lifting.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Intangible Assets and Business 
Combinations&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company adopted ASC 805,&amp;#160;&amp;#147;Business 
Combinations&amp;#148;,&amp;#160;and&#13;ASC 350,&amp;#160;&amp;#147;Goodwill 
and Other Intangible Assets&amp;#148;, effective June 2001 and revised in 
December 2007. ASC 805 requires&#13;the use of the purchase method of accounting
for any business combinations initiated after June 30, 2002, and further 
clarifies&#13;the criteria to recognize intangible assets separately from 
goodwill. Under ASC 350, goodwill and indefinite&amp;#8722;life 
intangible&#13;assets are no longer amortized, but are reviewed for impairment 
annually.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Oil &amp;#38; Gas 
Inventory&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company accounts for the oil &amp;#38; gas extracted 
from the ground&#13;and held in holding tanks prior to pickup and sale as oil 
&amp;#38; gas inventory. It is computed using the measurement of barrels&#13;and
is multiplied with the published oil purchase price
 from the customer that picks up and purchases our oil.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; 
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Concentrations
of Credit Risk&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times,
Serif; margin: 0"&gt;During the quarter ended June 30, 2016, the Company had no 
oil revenues&#13;and no accounts receivable.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; 
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Income 
Taxes&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-indent: 0pt"&gt;The Company applies ASC 740 which 
requires&#13;the asset and liability method of accounting for income taxes. The 
asset and liability method requires that the current or deferred&#13;tax 
consequences of all events recognized in the financial statements are measured 
by applying the provisions of enacted tax laws&#13;to determine the amount of 
taxes payable or refundable currently or in future years. Deferred tax assets 
are reviewed for recoverability&#13;and the Company records a valuation 
allowance to reduce its deferred tax assets when it is more likely than not that
all or some&#13;portion of the deferred tax assets will not be 
recovered.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company 
adopted ASC 740 at the beginning of fiscal year 2008.&#13;This interpretation 
requires recognition and measurement of uncertain tax positions using a 
&amp;#147;more-likely-than-not&amp;#148;&#13;approach, requiring the recognition
and measurement of uncertain tax positions. The adoption of ASC 740 had no 
material impact&#13;on the Company&amp;#146;s financial statements. Deferred 
taxes are provided on a liability method whereby deferred tax assets 
are&#13;recognized for deductible temporary differences and operating loss and 
tax credit carry forwards and deferred tax liabilities are&#13;recognized for 
taxable temporary differences. Temporary differences are the differences between
the reported amounts of assets&#13;and liabilities and their tax bases. Deferred
tax assets are reduced by a valuation allowance when, in the opinion of 
management,&#13;it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the 
deferred tax assets will to be realized. Deferred tax assets and 
liabilities&#13;are adjusted for the effects of changes in tax laws and rates on
the date of enactment&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock>

01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin:

the&#13;Company for unpaid wages and bonuses from previous years that were 
converted into Notes. The balances at June 30, 2016 and December&#13;31, 2015 
are $421,044 to Mr. Reichman and $206,670 to Mrs. Griffin, respectively. The 
notes bear interest at 5% are due at October&#13;1, 2017 and are 
unsecured.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0pt"&gt;Due to officers as of June 30, 
2016 and December&#13;31, 2015 totals $-0- and $164,105, respectively. These 
balances consist of net cash advances, and unpaid expense reimbursements&#13;due
to David Reichman. The payables and cash advances are unsecured, due on demand 
and do not bear interest. During the first Six&#13;months of 2016 Mr. Reichman 
advanced $206,216 to the Company to cover operating expenses, and was repaid 
$430,819. During the first&#13;Six months of 2015 Mr. Reichman advanced $52,635,
to the Company and was repaid $42,700. At June 30, 2016 and December 31, 
2015,&#13;the balances due Mr. Reichman are $-0- and $164,105, 
respectively.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times,

2016 and the year&#13;ended December 31, 2015, a board member advanced $3,000 
and $31,800, respectively. These totals consist of several small 
advances,&#13;each covered by separate notes that bear interest at 6%, are 
unsecured, and are due in October 2017. The total notes payable to&#13;this

    <us-gaap:CommitmentsAndContingenciesDisclosureTextBlock 
contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;During March 2013, the Company 
was named in an&#13;action pertaining to the 75% working interest in the Ownbey 
Lease.&lt;font style="color: #1F497D"&gt; &lt;/font&gt;Subsequent to the 
Company&amp;#146;s&#13;purchase of the assets and the termination of the 
operator a mechanics lien was filed against the property claiming 
approximately&#13;$267,000 in fees are due to the previous operator. An action 
is pending in the District Court of Chautauqua County, Kansas, 
captioned&#13;&lt;u&gt;Aesir Energy, Inc. vs. Amercian Resource Technologies, 
Inc.; Nancy Ownbey Archer; Jimmy Stephen Ownbey; Robbie Faye Butts; TREE&#13;TOP
INDUSTRIES, INC.; and TTII Oil &amp;#38; Gas, Inc.&lt;/u&gt; Management intends 
to vigorously contest AESIR&amp;#146;s claims and, at this&#13;point, settlement
appears unlikely. It has been presented in the County Court that some of 
ARUR&amp;#146;s Directors have acted without&#13;authorization in this matter, 
and TTII&amp;#146;s management is assessing how to proceed at this time. No 
monetary claims have been&#13;asserted against TTII or TTII Oil &amp;#38; Gas, 
Inc. The District Court of Chautauqua County, Kansas decided that the Board of 
American&#13;Resource Technologies, Inc., acted improperly and set aside the 
Acquisition Agreement as null and void. Management is consulting&#13;with legal
counsel to evaluate the company options.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;</us-

&amp;#145;Green&amp;#146; food sourcing and logistics business, working with

    <us-gaap:UseOfEstimates contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity&#13;with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America 
requires management to make estimates and assumptions&#13;that affect the 
reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial 
statements and the reported amounts of&#13;revenue and expenses during the 
reporting period. Actual results could differ from those 
estimates.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:UseOfEstimates>
    <us-gaap:DebtPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;In accordance with
FASB ASC 470-20, Accounting for Convertible Securities&#13;with Beneficial 
Conversion Features or Contingently Adjustable Conversion Ratios, we recognize 
the advantageous value of conversion&#13;rights attached to convertible 
debt.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Such rights give the debt holder the ability to convert
his debt into common stock&#13;at a price per share that is less than the 
trading price to the public on the day the loan is made to us. The beneficial 
value&#13;is calculated as the intrinsic value (the market price of the stock at
the commitment date in excess of the conversion rate) of&#13;the beneficial 
conversion feature of the debentures and related accruing interest, and is 
recorded as a discount to the related&#13;debt and an addition to additional 
paid in capital.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The discount is amortized over the remaining
outstanding period&#13;of related debt using the straight-line 
method.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:DebtPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock 
contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;No accounting pronouncements were issued during the 
second quarter&#13;of 2016 that would have a material effect on the accounting 
policies of the Company when adopted.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:OilAndGasPropertiesPolicyPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-
01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;The Company utilizes the full cost method of accounting for oil 
and&#13;gas activities. Under this method, subject to a limitation based on 
estimated value, all costs associated with property acquisition,&#13;exploration
and development, including costs of unsuccessful exploration; are capitalized 
within a cost center. No gain or loss&#13;is recognized upon the sale or 
abandonment of undeveloped or producing oil and gas interests unless the sale 
represents a significant&#13;portion of oil and gas interests and the gain 
significantly alters the relationship between capitalized costs and proved oil 
and&#13;gas reserves of the cost center. Depreciation, depletion and 
amortization of oil and gas interests are computed on the units 
of&#13;production method based on proved reserves. Amortizable costs include 
estimates of future development costs of proved 
undeveloped&#13;reserves.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Capitalized costs of oil and gas interests may not 
exceed an amount&#13;equal to the present value, discounted at 10%, of the 
estimated future net cash flows from proved oil and gas reserves plus 
the&#13;cost, or estimated fair market value, if lower, of unproved interests. 
Should capitalized costs exceed this ceiling, an impairment&#13;is recognized. 
The present value of estimated future net cash flows is computed by applying 
average prices, in the preceding twelve&#13;months, of oil and gas to estimated 
future production of proved oil and gas reserves as of year-end, less estimated 
future expenditures&#13;to be incurred in developing and producing the proved 
reserves and assuming continuation of existing economic 
conditions.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The oil and gas interests were purchased with the 
issuance of 46,685,300&#13;shares and were valued at market value at the grant 
date as $513,538. However at December 31, 2012, due to a mechanics lien 
and&#13;impairment of title to the assets, the Company impaired the recorded 
cost, leaving no value associated with the acquisition. The&#13;Company recorded
an impairment on long lived assets in the amount of $513,538.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:OilAndGasPropertiesPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:AssetRetirementObligationsPolicy contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-
06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company follows FASB ASC 410-20&lt;i&gt; &amp;#34;Accounting for 
Asset&#13;Retirement Obligations,&amp;#34;&lt;/i&gt; which addresses financial 
accounting and reporting for obligations associated with the retirement&#13;of 
tangible long-lived assets and the associated asset retirement 
costs.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;FASB ASC 410-20 requires recognition of the present 
value of obligations&#13;associated with the retirement of tangible long-lived 
assets in the period in which it is incurred. The liability is 
capitalized&#13;as part of the related long-lived asset's carrying 
amount.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Over time, accretion of the liability is recognized 
as an operating&#13;expense and the capitalized cost is depreciated over the 
expected useful life of the related asset. The Company's asset 
retirement&#13;obligations are related to the plugging, dismantlement, removal, 
site reclamation and similar activities of its oil and gas 
exploration&#13;activities.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; width: 
100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    
&lt;td&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;The asset retirement obligation is 
as follows:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;
&lt;td colspan="2" style="text-align: center"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    
&lt;td&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    
&lt;td colspan="2" style="text-align: center"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    
&lt;td&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: 
bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="2" style="border-bottom: black 1pt solid; text-align: 
center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;6/30/2016&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="2" style="border-bottom: black 1pt solid; text-align:

    <us-gaap:CostMethodInvestmentsPolicy contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-
30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company&amp;#160;accounts for its investment in private entities&#13;using the 
equity method for investments where the Company&amp;#146;s shares held are in 
excess of 20% of the outstanding&amp;#160;shares&#13;of the 
investee.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Company acquired a 25% equity investment in 
three entities from Brazil as part of the assets of&#13;the ARUR acquisition in 
December 2012. Due to the inactivity of the entities, the Company did not 
allocate any purchase price to&#13;these investments. The Company 
evaluates&amp;#160;its cost in investments for impairment of value 
annually.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If cost investments&#13;become marketable they 
are&amp;#160;reclassified to Marketable Securities-Available for 
Sale.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0"

    <us-gaap:MarketableSecuritiesPolicy contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-
30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company purchased marketable securities during 2012, 2015 and&#13;2016. The 
Company's marketable securities are classified as &amp;#34;available for 
sale&amp;#34;. Accordingly, the Company originally&#13;recognizes the shares at 
the market value purchased. The shares are evaluated quarterly using the 
specific identification method.&#13;Any unrealized holding gains or losses are 
reported as Other Comprehensive Income and as a separate component of 
stockholder's&#13;equity. Realized gains and losses are included in earnings. 
Also other than temporary impairments are recorded as a loss on 
marketable&#13;securities in the statements of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;Marketable securities are as follows at June&#13;30, 
2016:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;

gaap:MarketableSecuritiesPolicy>
    <us-gaap:FairValueOfFinancialInstrumentsPolicy contextRef="From2016-01-
01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;On January 1, 2008, the Company adopted ASC 820, &amp;#147;Fair 
Value&#13;Measurements&amp;#148;&lt;i&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/i&gt;ASC 820 defines 
fair value, establishes a three-level valuation hierarchy for disclosures of 
fair&#13;value measurement and enhances disclosure requirements for fair value 
measures. The three levels are defined as follows:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="width: 100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: 
top"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-
bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 
5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-
left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&#13;        &lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;o&lt;/p&gt;&#13;        &lt;p style="font: 8pt Times
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 94%; 
border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: 
#BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Level 1 inputs to the 
valuation methodology are quoted prices (unadjusted) for identical assets or 
liabilities in active 
markets.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="width: 100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: 
top"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-
bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 
5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-
left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;font 
style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;o&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width:
94%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-
bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Level 2 inputs to
the valuation methodology include quoted prices for similar assets and 
liabilities in active markets, and inputs that are observable for the asset or 
liability, either directly or indirectly, for substantially the full term of the
financial 
instrument.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0" 
cellpadding="0" style="width: 100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: 
top"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-
bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 
5%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-
left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;font 
style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;o&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width:
94%; border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-right: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-
bottom: #BFBFBF 1.5pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; font: 12pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Level 3 inputs to
the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant to the fair 
measurement.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The carrying amounts reported in the balance sheets 
for cash and&#13;cash equivalents, and current liabilities each qualify as 
financial instruments and are a reasonable estimate of fair value because&#13;of
the short period of time between the origination of such instruments and their 
expected realization and their current market&#13;rate of interest. The carrying
value of notes payable approximates fair value because negotiated terms and 
conditions are consistent&#13;with current market rates as of June 30, 2016 and 
December 31, 2015.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;Marketable securities are reported at the quoted and
listed market&#13;rates of the securities held at the period 
end.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-indent: 45pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The following 
table presents the 
Company&amp;#146;s&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Marketable&#13;securities and Notes 
Payable within the fair value hierarchy utilized to measure fair value on a 
recurring basis as of June 30,&#13;2016 and December 31, 
2015:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table
cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="font: 12pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
width: 100%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="border-top: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; border-left: #BFBFBF 1pt 
solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="2" style="border-bottom:
black 1pt solid; text-align: center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Level 1&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="2" style="border-bottom: black 1pt solid; text-align: 
center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Level 
2&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="padding-bottom: 
1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="2" style="border-bottom:
black 1pt solid; text-align: center"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Level 3&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr 
style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 64%; border-
left: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;Marketable 
Securities &amp;#150; 2016&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 
1%; padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width:
1%; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 9%; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: 
right"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 
8pt"&gt;115,428&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%; 
padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%;
padding-bottom: 1.5pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td style="width: 1%;
border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
style="width: 9%; border-bottom: #BFBFBF 1pt solid; text-align: 
right"&gt;&lt;font style="font-size: 8pt"&gt;-0-&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;

    <us-gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-
30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align:
justify"&gt;The accompanying consolidated financial statements&#13;include the 
accounts of the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiaries, NetThruster, Inc., 
BioEnergy Applied Technologies Inc.,&#13;GoHealthMD, Inc., MLN, Inc., Eye Care 
Centers International, Inc., GoHealthMD Nano Pharmaceuticals, Inc., TTI 
Strategic Acquisitions&#13;and&amp;#160;Equity Group, Inc.&amp;#160;and TTII Oil
&amp;#38; Gas, Inc.&amp;#160;All subsidiaries of the Company except TTII Oil 
&amp;#38; Gas, Inc.,&#13;currently have no financial activity. All significant 
inter-company balances and transactions have been 
eliminated.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:ConsolidationPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-
01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0"&gt;The Company considers all highly liquid investments with an 
original&#13;maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents. Cash and 
cash equivalents are maintained with major financial institutions&#13;in the U 
S. Deposits held with these banks at times exceed $250,000 of insurance provided
on such deposits. The Company has not&#13;experienced any losses in such 
accounts and believes that it is not exposed to any significant credit risk on 
cash and cash equivalents.&#13;There were no cash equivalents at June 30, 2016 
and December 31, 2015.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-
gaap:ReceivablesTradeAndOtherAccountsReceivableAllowanceForDoubtfulAccountsPolic
y contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company regularly assesses the 
collectability of its accounts&#13;receivable, and considers receivables with 
aging exceeding 120 days to be potentially uncollectible. Management will 
analyze the&#13;need for an allowance for doubtful accounts at that time. As of 
June 30, 2016 and December 31, 2015, there are no allowances 
recorded.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ReceivablesTradeAndOtherAccountsReceivableAllowanceForDoubtfulAccountsPolic
y>
    <us-gaap:ShareBasedCompensationOptionAndIncentivePlansPolicy 
contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The Company accounts for stock-based compensation in
accordance with&#13;the provisions of ASC 718.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;ASC 718 
requires all share-based payments to employees, including grants of employee 
stock&#13;options, to be recognized in the financial statements based on the 
grant-date fair value of the award. That cost will be recognized&#13;over the 
period during which an employee is required to provide service in exchange for 
the reward- known as the requisite service&#13;period. No compensation cost is 
recognized for equity instruments for which employees do not render the 
requisite service. The&#13;grant-date fair value of employee share options and 
similar instruments are estimated using the Black Scholes option-pricing 
model&#13;adjusted for the unique characteristics of those 
instruments.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Equity instruments issued to
non-employees are&#13;recorded at their fair values as determined in accordance 
with ASC 718 and ASC 595, &amp;#147;Accounting for Equity Instruments 
That&#13;Are Issued to Other Than Employees for Acquiring, or in Conjunction 
with Selling Goods and Services&amp;#148;, and are periodically&#13;revalued as 
the stock options vest and are recognized as expense over the related service 
period.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ShareBasedCompensationOptionAndIncentivePlansPolicy>
    <us-gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2016-01-01to2016-
06-30">&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0"&gt;The 
Company calculates earnings per share in accordance with ASC&#13;260, 
&amp;#147;Computation of Earnings Per Share.&amp;#148; Basic loss per share is 
computed by dividing net income (loss) by the weighted-average&#13;number of 
shares of common stock outstanding during the period. Diluted earnings (loss) 
per share gives effect to dilutive convertible&#13;securities, options, warrants
and other potential common stock outstanding during the period; only in periods 
in which such effect&#13;is dilutive. For 2016 and 2015, no common equivalent 
shares were excluded from the calculation and as of June 30, 2016, there 
are&#13;not stock equivalents existing. The ESOP shares issued during 2012 and 
2011 have also been excluded from the calculation as they&#13;were issued but 
not outstanding.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 8pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellspacing="0"
